o reduce greenhouse emissions in Mumbai, the bus fleet is being upgraded to run on 10% biodiesel, and compact natural gas, in line with the National Urban Transport Policy.189 Jakarta has implemented rapid bus transit corridors, and is investigating a mass rapid transit (MRT) rail line in an attempt to reduce congestion on its roads, improve air quality and reduce 183 (Dodman, Urban Form, Greenhouse Gas Emissions and Climate Vulnerability 2010) 184 (BPS: Statistics Indonesia 2010) 185 (Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai 2009, 32) 186 (Lebel, et al. 2007, 66) 187 (Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai 2009, 157) 188 (Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai 2009, 156) 189 (Municipal Corporation of Greater Mumbai 2009, 155) 46 emissions. This is in line with the National Climate Change Sectoral Roadmap, but particularly the city\u2019s Medium Term Development Plan 2007 \u2013 2012 which encourages the implementation of a rapid, integrated bus system, and development of the MRT system. Table 4: Number of Registered Motor Vehicles, Jakarta, excl. Army, Police and Diplomatic Jakarta 2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 Motor cycles 1,813,13 6 2,257,19 4 3,316,90 0 3,940,70 0 4,647,43 5 5,310,06 8 5,974,17 3 6,765,72 3 Passenger Vans 1,130,49 6 1,195,87 1 1,529,82 4 1,645,30 6 1,766,80 1 1,835,65 3 1,916,46 9 2,034,94 3 Cargo Cars 347,443 366,221 464,748 488,517 499,581 504,727 518,991 538,731 Buses 253,648 254,849 315,652 316,396 316,502 317,050 318,332 308,528 TOTAL 3,544,72 3 4,074,13 5 5,627,12 4 6,390,91 9 7,230,31 9 7,967,49 8 8,727,96 5 9,647,92 5 Source: Statistics Jakarta, http://jakarta.bps.go.id/index_e.html Table 5: Number of Registered Vehicles in Mumbai Mumbai 2000 2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2Wheelers 407,306 440,517 475,352 527,108 584,180 NA 714,209 792,512 3Wheelers 97,565 101,914 104,829 98,527 102,224 NA 104,899 104,862 Cars/jeeps 329,546 344,870 353,417 366,805 384,258 NA 436,213 464,139 Taxis 58,696 62,447 63,679 54,809 56,459 NA 57,3