 gender, age, religion, employment or other criteria. a) India Project/Program Title Resilient Flood Loss Response Systems for Vulnerable Populations in Mumbai: A Neglected Alternative Organisation/Author Monalisa Chatterjee Period 2010 What is Vulnerability Assessment approach undertaken? As this is a PhD study, the approach taken develops its own framework, drawing on several theoretical approaches. It is based on a combination of quantitative and qualitative data gathering. It has 3 levels: 1) a national level analysis of hazard events and mitigation policy; 2) city level review of flood mitigation strategies; and 3) a household scale assessment of flood risk, vulnerability and coping strategies; Methodology included: Survey of 50 households in the area via a detailed questionnaire; Focus groups conducted in both communities; Key informant interviews; Observations and visits; Project/Program Title Flood Risks, Climate Change Impacts and Adaptation Benefits in Mumbai Organisation/Author Stephane Hallegate, Henriet Fanny, Anand Patwhardan, K. Narayanan, Subimal Ghosh, Subhankar Karmakar, Unmesh Patnaik, Abhijat Abhayankar, Sanjib Pohit, Jan Corfee-Morlot, Celine Herweijer, Nicola Ranger, Sumana Bhattacharya, Murthy Bachu, Satya Priya, K. Dhore, Farhat Rafique, P. Mathur, Nicolas Naville Period 2010 What is Vulnerability Assessment approach undertaken? Impacts based adaptation assessment: Characterising current level of vulnerability and potential future sensitivities, quantifying relevant risks, identifying adaptation options. Sample size of surveys about 530 households, approx. 50 households across 11 wards; Interviews with \u201chead of household\u201d, which in over 85% of cases was male. Project/Program Title Floods Risk Reduction in Livelihood Risks: Thoughts and Insights from Mumbai Organisation/Author H. Takano and S. Sammadar Period 2010 What is Vulnerability Assessment approach undertaken? Face to face, structured and semi-structured interviews; based on sampling, targeting head of family, but if not available, then other respondents were chosen. Also observation, unstructured interview of field engineers, local political and religious leaders. 80 b) Indonesia Project/Program Title Vulnerability Assessment of Jakarta and Java Island Organisation/Author Institute of Essential Services Reform Period 2010 What is Vulnerability Assessment approach undertaken? This research combines both top down and bottom up approaches.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b6ce4aa2-9c26-42cb-ac6a-31f4a158e4ca": {"__data__": {"id_": "b6ce4aa2-9c26-42cb-ac6a-31f4a158e4ca", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2012/06", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "APHDR Technical Background Paper 2012/06", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2012/06", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "146a4e2f471fbbc9b2305bb36ef43f0c44b1ab3fbdd899d07edf526c63b2df42"}, "2": {"node_id": "d4277541-a659-4a49-a196-451c806d6698", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2012/06", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ee39fc04d433d8aac2c894cfd5e7fd454b45019502c06fccc0ca7dd687a118e8"}}, "hash": "21caab1933b8c473b9353f552bfcf6eacfb1b649a6779171c4d16ea18b3218bd", "text": "This research combines both top down and bottom up approaches. The top down approach is represented by the climate modeling method using the Meteorological Research Institute (MRI) model of Japan that includes scenario A1B, A2, and B1 which will be used to project the future climate risks of Java Island and DKI Jakarta province. Meanwhile the bottom up approach is done through field research using Participatory Rural Appraisal (PRA) concepts and tools to look at the current climate risks and present adaptation strategies including the challenges at urban coastal community, called Kelurahan Kamal Muara. Findings from these two approaches will be used for triangulation which will improve the validity and reliability of the results. Project/Program Title Vulnerability Assessment and Coping Mechanism related to Floods in Urban Areas: A Community Based Case Study in Kampung Melayu, Jakarta Organisation/Author Masters Degree Thesis, Ms. Mone Iye Cornelia (University of Gadjah Mada, Yogyakarta) Period", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "11a3b1f0-582a-4354-87e6-f349c8ecd5a0": {"__data__": {"id_": "11a3b1f0-582a-4354-87e6-f349c8ecd5a0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2012/06", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "APHDR Technical Background Paper 2012/06", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2012/06", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a48352aa0cf1fd9576d8031ed6720a5cdae8077abccfd328c85d8d4f45834f7e"}, "3": {"node_id": "5a56e6ec-f752-45b4-98fb-c1a47adbd172", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/aphdr-technical-background-paper-2012/06", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "16ceaf9066892ec74eaae27cc603317210f5b401b831db5fb3bb2892ef9139b1"}}, "hash": "b5a33c9733144886ffd9bb17f5f5ed58d64c4da666299599bf1c73af462a6b4f", "text": "2008 What is Vulnerability Assessment approach undertaken? This research tries to explore the vulnerability as well as the capacity for flood management based on local people\u2019s perception. There were 83 households interviewed using a questionnaire. Certain elements of risk related with physical and socio-economic aspects were identified. Physical information concerned the building structure and building contents. Several socio-economic were used as key indicators to analyse the vulnerability of people. In addition, information about flood occurrence, and existing coping mechanisms based on people\u2019s perception are also discussed in this research. Project/Program Title Socio-Economic Aspect of Vulnerability Assessment due to Sea Level Rise in Jakarta Organisation/Author Master Degree Thesis, Mr. Awanda Sentosa (University of Indonesia, Jakarta) Period 2010 What is Vulnerability Assessment approach undertaken? This research focuses on socio-economic vulnerability assessment and the development of a socio-economic vulnerability index due to sea level rise. The research covers the following components: (i) identification of disaster event (event, predictability, duration, area), (ii) Socio-economic vulnerability index (land use, poverty index, population density, number of people affected by sea flood, the impact of sea level rise), (iii) factors incluencing vulnerability (education level, employment, asset tenureship, income, social and source of information) 81 The research was dev